# Evidence

A nice study shows that particularly good teachers tend to use a variety of methods, some of which don't work [fill in ...]

# Why variety is good

1. Makes the students think about what the hell the teacher is doing.  This is similar to the advantages of making a few mistakes (e.g. in calculations).

2. Postpones burn-out.

3. Variety improves the teacher-student bond by making each teaching experience more personal.  Maybe this is too similar to point 1 to deserve a separate point.
